metadata.name: Good Enough #407
metadata.description:
I tamed a 3D volumetric fractal to do this. Not an easy task, several hours of fine-tuning trying to reach what I want to express and please my eyes. Making sure that every iteration not only gives interesting results but they are part of the same concept. But when to stop? When it's finished? Well, maybe it never is. We are imperfect beings and so our art is. Everything always could be better, but sometimes we have to stop and accept that it's over, that it's the best we can do. And the best we can do it's good enough.

I want to dedicate this piece to Xiomara Elizabeth Martini.

metadata.name: Geometric Motion #45
metadata.description:
Inspired by minimalist graphic designs, this work is an exploration of combinations for simple geometrical shapes. The shapes slide under others, go out of view and reappear in an ever-changing canvas.

On a grid of 4 to 7 cells we place triangles, squares, and circles of different sizes. Their color and draw order are determined by their initial row placement. They move around freely inside the canvas indefinitely, showing a quasi-infinite number of combinations.

There are 10 possible colors, with 2 that are very rare that change the blend method to "exclusion" or "difference".

Coded with p5js

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2021

metadata.name: Randos #72
metadata.description:
Meet Randos. Generative PFP ready pictures. Each Rando has unique features and a rando-id made up of a random 3 letter word + a number. See if you can get a scrabble-friendly word. Each Rando also has a frequently used word/phrase. Inspired by the Xcopy style flashing imagery, glitch art, and color pallete.


Click on the image to save a frame.
Please mint only a few as it's a free mint.

metadata.name: Hyperspace interface #149
metadata.description:
Another one of my belowed GUI in retro-style
Fasten your seat belts, team! We are entering the hyperspace!

IMPORTANT! 
The work has two modes. At 100% page scale it is more stylized as a blurry retro.
You can zoom in to 125% for a crisper, cleaner look. This is done with CTRL + MOUSE SCROLL or with CTRL + "+"
You also need to refresh the page after zooming!

ALSO!
The best view is obtained in the aspect ratio of 1:1 or 4:3, in 16:9 the work requires too many resources and has nothing to show.
